function minStopCosts(regular, express, expressCost) {
    const n = regular.length;
    const costs = new Array(n);
    let regular_sum = 0, express_sum = expressCost;

    for (let i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        regular_sum += regular[i];
        express_sum += express[i];
        costs[i] = Math.min(regular_sum, express_sum + expressCost);
    }

    return costs;
}
```

    The algorithm computes the minimum cost for reaching each stop `i` from the start `0`. We maintain two sums, `regular_sum` and `express_sum`, representing the costs spent on both routes.

1. Initialize `regular_sum` to `0` and `express_sum` to `expressCost`, because we always begin from the regular route and have to pay the cost to transfer to the express route.
2. Iterate over stops from `0` to `n-1`.
3. In each iteration, update `regular_sum` by adding the cost to move to the next stop using the regular route, and update `express_sum` by adding the cost to move to the next stop using the express route.
4. For each stop `i`, the minimum cost is the minimum of either staying on the regular route or transferring to the express route and moving to the next stop. So, `costs[i] = min(regular_sum, express_sum + expressCost)`.
5. After the loop, return the array `costs`.

The time complexity is O(n) and the space complexity is O(n).

